      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cli): document Commander rawArgs internal API dependency in action-reparse.ts",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdd a comment documenting that `rawArgs` is accessed via an unsafe cast because it is not part of Commander's public TypeScript interface. Makes the technical debt visible so future maintainers know the risk.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #83893\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** `rawArgs` accessed via unsafe cast to Commander internal; no runtime assertion or documentation explaining the risk.\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS, Node v22.22.3, latest upstream/main\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n  1. Run unit tests (exercises real Commander objects through reparseProgramFromActionArgs):\n  ```bash\n  node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/cli/program/action-reparse.test.ts\n  ```\n  2. Verify the comment is present in the source:\n  ```bash\n  grep -A4 \"rawArgs.*Commander\" src/cli/program/action-reparse.ts\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix (copied live output):**\n\n```\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/cli/program/action-reparse.test.ts\n\n RUN  v4.1.7 /Users/truman/openclaw\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  5 passed (5)\n   Start at  21:38:31\n   Duration  445ms (transform 386ms, setup 256ms, import 15ms, tests 73ms, environment 0ms)\n\n[test] passed 1 Vitest shard in 4.56s\n\n$ grep -A4 \"rawArgs.*Commander\" src/cli/program/action-reparse.ts\n  // `rawArgs` is Commander's internal argv slice for the sub-command.  It is not\n  // part of the public TypeScript interface, so it is accessed via a cast.  If\n  // Commander removes or renames this property in a future version, the cast\n  // silently returns undefined and parseArgv falls back to the reconstructed\n  // fallbackArgv — which may omit flags passed positionally.\n  const rawArgs = (root as Command & { rawArgs?: string[] }).rawArgs;\n```\n\nThe comment is in place and all 5 tests pass, including:\n- `\"falls back to fallbackArgv when Commander rawArgs is missing from parent command\"` — simulates Commander version without rawArgs, verifies clean fallback to reconstructed argv\n- `\"uses action command name + args as fallback argv\"` — normal case with rawArgs present\n- `\"falls back to action args without command name when action has no name\"` — rawArgs undefined, works correctly\n- `\"preserves explicit parent command options in fallback argv\"` — parent command options preserved\n- `\"uses program root when action command is missing\"` — program root fallback\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** Comment documents the unsafe cast and fallback behavior. All 5 tests pass, including the new test that explicitly verifies rawArgs=undefined fallback.\n- **What was not tested:** N/A — the fix is a documentation comment; no runtime behavior changes.\n- **Proof limitations or environment constraints:** The `reparseProgramFromActionArgs` function is exercised through real Commander `Command` objects. The test mocks `buildParseArgv` to isolate the parsing logic, which is the standard pattern used by all other test files in `src/cli/program/`.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\n**Which commands did you run?**\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/cli/program/action-reparse.test.ts\n# 5 passed (1 test file)\n```\n\n**What regression coverage was added or updated?**\nAdded `\"falls back to fallbackArgv when Commander rawArgs is missing from parent command\"` — explicitly tests the unsafe cast returning undefined when Commander removes `rawArgs`.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\n**Did user-visible behavior change?** No\n**Did config, environment, or migration behavior change?** No\n**Did security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change?** No\n**What is the highest-risk area?** None — documentation comment + test only.\n**How is that risk mitigated?** N/A\n\n## Current review state\n\n**What is the next action?** Maintainer review after re-review.\n**What is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?** None.\n\n---\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Code <noreply@anthropic.com>\n",
